description: From Latin inaquatus, past participle of inaquo (“to make into water”), from in- (“in”) + aqua (“water”).

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Embodied in, or changed into, water.
examples: But forasmuch as he is joined to the bread but sacramentally, there followeth no impanation thereof, no more than the Holy Ghost is inaquate, that is to say, made water, being sacramentally joined to the water in baptism
